# 📦 SUMMARY  
# These commands connect to a remote server via SSH, update the package list, install Docker if missing, run a Jenkins container with persistent storage and port mapping, and verify the container is running.  
# Language/Platform: Bash (Linux) and SSH  
# What you'll learn: Remote server management, package installation, running Jenkins in Docker with volume persistence and port mapping  
# Outcome: Jenkins continuous integration server running in a Docker container accessible on ports 8080 and 50000 with persistent data storage  
# Why this matters: Enables easy setup of Jenkins on a remote server, facilitating automated builds and deployments with data persistence  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Connect to Remote Server via SSH  
# ------------------------------  
ssh root@<droplet-ip>  
# ✅ What it does: Opens a secure shell session to the remote server as root at the given IP  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Provides command-line access to manage the remote server  
# 🔄 Equivalent PowerShell command:  
# ssh root@<droplet-ip>  
# Explanation: Works the same in PowerShell with OpenSSH installed  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Update Package List on Remote Server  
# ------------------------------  
apt update  
# ✅ What it does: Refreshes the package database to ensure the latest package versions are available  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Important before installing new software to get updated versions and dependencies  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Install Docker if Not Present  
# ------------------------------  
apt install docker.io  
# ✅ What it does: Installs the Docker engine package on the remote server  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Ensures Docker is available to run containers like Jenkins  
# 🔄 Equivalent PowerShell command: N/A (runs on remote Linux server)  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Start Jenkins Container with Docker  
# ------------------------------  
docker run \                     # ✅ What it does: Starts a new container from a given image.  
                                 # 🧠 Why it matters: Containers let you run Jenkins without installing it directly on your host.  

-p 8080:8080 \                   # ✅ What it does: Maps your machine’s port 8080 → container’s port 8080.  
                                 # 🧠 Why it matters: Lets you access Jenkins UI in your browser at http://localhost:8080.  

-p 50000:50000 \                 # ✅ What it does: Maps your machine’s port 50000 → container’s port 50000.  
                                 # 🧠 Why it matters: Required if Jenkins agents (remote helpers) connect to this controller.  

-d \                             # ✅ What it does: Runs container in detached (background) mode.  
                                 # 🧠 Why it matters: Lets you continue using your terminal while Jenkins runs in the background.  

-v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home \   # ✅ What it does: Creates a Docker volume named `jenkins_home` for persistence.  
                                      # 🧠 Why it matters: Saves Jenkins jobs, users, and plugins so data isn’t lost if the container stops.  

jenkins/jenkins:lts              # ✅ What it does: Uses the official Jenkins Long-Term Support (LTS) image.  
                                 # 🧠 Why it matters: Ensures stability and reliability in production setups.  
                                 
docker run -p 8080:8080 -p 50000:50000 -d -v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home jenkins/jenkins:lts


# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 SECTION TITLE: Verify Running Containers  
# ------------------------------  
docker ps  
# ✅ What it does: Lists all currently running Docker containers to confirm Jenkins is running  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Quick health check to ensure Jenkins container is up  
# 🔄 Equivalent PowerShell command: Same command works in PowerShell  

# ------------------------------  
# ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS  
# ------------------------------  
# - Replace `<droplet-ip>` with your actual server IP address.  
# - You might need `sudo` before `apt` or `docker` commands if not running as root.  
# - Use `docker logs <container_id>` to see Jenkins startup logs if it takes time to be ready.  
# - To stop Jenkins container: `docker stop <container_id>`.  
# - Access Jenkins UI via http://<droplet-ip>:8080 after container is up.  
